Angular 22 ships selectorless components as stable, and the ergonomic win is real, but there are structural trade-offs worth understanding before you migrate a large codebase.
Press enter or click to view image in full size

Every Angular project I have worked on for the last four years carries the same mild tax: you define a component, give it a selector, add it to imports, and then type the selector string again in the template. Three places for one thing. Angular 22 removes that redundancy with selectorless components, now stable in the June 2026 release. The next active development branch, 22.1.0-next.4, shipped July 1 with continued refinements to the input-writes migration tooling that underpins this change.
I want to be concrete about what this actually means, because the announcement understates both the win and the cost.
The Pattern You Are Replacing
Here is a typical component consumption in Angular 21 and below:
// user-card.component.ts
@Component({
selector: 'app-user-card', // string defined here
standalone: true,
templateUrl: './user-card.component.html',
})
export class UserCardComponent {
@Input() userId!: string; // classic decorator input
